Data Visualization Workshop Slides

Christopher Kinson

What is data visualization?

Data visualization is a image, plot, chart, or graphic generated from data. Typically data visualizations can be saved as image files such as .png, .jpg, and .pdf. Knowing how to create data visualizations that are informative is important any data worker.

Tidyverse for data visualization

The tidyverse is a collection of R packages and a workflow for working with data. The tidyverse is supported by Posit (the company that made RStudio). See more details at https://www.tidyverse.org/. The ggplot2 package is most useful for data visualization, or data viz for short. Its main function is ggplot(), which creates a blank canvas for any data viz.

With ggplot, we will consider each graphical element as a layer. One of the tidyverse’s most useful operators for data viz is the addition operator + as it allows for new layers to be added to a data viz.

First, we’ll import the the City of Urbana’s Rental Inspection Grades Listing Data with the read_csv() function and print a snapshot of it.

Macro elements

These Macro elements are needed for any data viz. Let’s dive into each one using the rentalsData.

  • Narrative

  • Plot type

  • Title

  • Axes

Narrative

Considering the narrative of your data viz is crucial to the final product meeting your expectations. Thinking about the narrative also allows for clear communication in the data viz to your audience.

1. You need to know your audience.

  • Audiences can be very detail-oriented, big-picture-oriented, or anywhere in between.

  • You should adjust your narrative and resulting data visualization for your specific audience.

2. What do you want the audience to know or do?

  • Think about the data and information you want to share.

  • If your data doesn’t have that information, consider where you might source that missing information.

3. How you will you deliver what you want the audience to know?

  • Consider what needs to happen in order for the visualization to be interpreted well. Do those things.

  • Creating simple storyboards with pen and paper will help in organizing your narrative and resulting data viz.

Plot type: Scatter plot

Typically, scatter plots are useful when plotting two numeric vectors. Scatter plots can be added as a geometric layer with the function geom_point(). The aes() function is for adding aesthetics, such as which variables correspond to certain axes, color, and size.

rentalsData %>%
  filter(!is.na(`Expiration Date`), `Expiration Date` < "2023-01-01") %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = `Inspection Date`, y = `Expiration Date`))

Plot type: Series plot

Series plots (aka “index plots” aka “time series plots”) are plots of a single vector of values that have a time dimension. Series plots are best visualized with lines as the geometric layer. Hence, we can use the geom_line() function.

rentalsData %>%
  count(`Inspection Date`) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x = `Inspection Date`, y= n))

Plot type: Bar plot

We can create a bar plot using either geom_bar() or geom_col() functions. The geom_bar() function displays bars based on values directly in the data frame. The geom_col() function displays bars based on summarized data.

rentalsData %>%
  count(Grade) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_col(mapping = aes(x = Grade, y = n))

Title

we use a title to generalize the data viz, but at times, we may want to point out a particular detail. In any case, the title is created using the title= argument of the labs() function.

rentalsData %>%
  count(`Inspection Date`) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x = `Inspection Date`, y= n)) +
  labs(title="Number of Inspections on Each Date")

Axes

Axes are crucial for understanding the scale of the information being plotted and the context of the units measured. You should have noticed that the plots shown above have axis labels, ranges of values, and tick marks for certain values.

For example, we can label the horizontal and vertical axes using the x= and y= arguments, respectively, in the labs() function. Also, we can change the range of values shown in the axes using the xlim= and ylim= arguments of the coord_cartesian() function.

library(glue)
rentalsData %>%
  count(`Inspection Date`) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x = `Inspection Date`, y= n)) +
  labs(title="Number of Inspections on Each Date",
       y="Count",
       x=glue('Dates between {range(rentalsData$`Inspection Date`)[1]} and {range(rentalsData$`Inspection Date`)[2]}' )
) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,25))

If we wanted even more control over the axes’ lines, tick marks, and range of values, we can hide or suppress the default axes by setting an argument’s value to element_blank() within the theme() function.

  • suppressing the label of the ticks using the axis.text=element_blank() of the theme() function
    • specific to the horizontal axis axis.text.x=element_blank() of the theme() function
    • specific to the vertical axis axis.text.y=element_blank() of the theme() function
rentalsData %>%
  count(`Inspection Date`) %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(mapping=aes(x = `Inspection Date`, y= n)) +
  labs(title="Number of Inspections on Each Date",
       y="Count",
       x=glue('Dates between {range(rentalsData$`Inspection Date`)[1]} and {range(rentalsData$`Inspection Date`)[2]}' )
) +
  coord_cartesian(ylim=c(0,25)) +
  theme(axis.text=element_blank())

  • suppressing the tick marks using the axis.ticks=element_blank() of the theme() function
    • specific to the horizontal axis axis.ticks.x=element_blank() of the theme() function
    • specific to the vertical axis axis.ticks.y=element_blank() of the theme() function

  theme(axis.ticks.y=element_blank())

Micro Elements

There’s a wealth of details that can be added or adjusted to plots in base R. The details below are in my opinion, the Micro elements that every data visualization should address:

Plotting characters
Color and transparency
Width and size
Quantity of plots

Removing clutter
Employing visual hierarchy

Removing Clutter

Clutter is any visual thing that does not increase the audience’s understanding.

Here’s an example using the rentalsData, where we want to map the properties and guide the audience to particular information. In order to get that data, we use string manipulation for additional data wrangling.

Cluttered.

Coordinates<-str_split(rentalsData$`Mappable Address`, "\\\n", simplify = TRUE)

Coordinates[,1] <- str_replace(Coordinates[,1],"1\\s2","1/2")

Coordinates <- as_tibble(Coordinates) %>%
  mutate(City="Urbana", State="IL") %>%
  select(-V2)
## Warning: The `x` argument of `as_tibble.matrix()` must have unique column names if
## `.name_repair` is omitted as of tibble 2.0.0.
## ℹ Using compatibility `.name_repair`.
## This warning is displayed once every 8 hours.
## Call `lifecycle::last_lifecycle_warnings()` to see where this warning was
## generated.
Coordinates00 <- str_remove_all(Coordinates$V3, "\\)|\\,|\\(")
Coordinates000 <- str_split(Coordinates00, " ", simplify = TRUE)

rentalsData2 <- rentalsData %>%
  mutate(Coordinates01 = as.numeric(Coordinates000[,1]),
Coordinates02 = as.numeric(Coordinates000[,2]))

c01 <- ifelse(rentalsData2$Coordinates01<0,rentalsData2$Coordinates02,rentalsData2$Coordinates01)
c02 <- ifelse(rentalsData2$Coordinates02>0,rentalsData2$Coordinates01,rentalsData2$Coordinates02)

rentalsData3 <- rentalsData2 %>%
  mutate(Latitude = c01, Longitude = c02, City = Coordinates$City, State = Coordinates$State) %>%
  select(-c(`Mappable Address`,Coordinates01,Coordinates02))

rm(c01,c02,Coordinates00,Coordinates,rentalsData2)
#gc()
rentalsData3 %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Longitude, y=Latitude)) +
  labs(title = "Urbana Rental Properties")

Less cluttered.

rentalsData3 %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Longitude, y=Latitude),color="lightgray") +
  labs(title = "Urbana Rental Properties") +
  geom_point(x=-88.227244, y=40.109399, color=rgb(19/255,41/255,75/255), alpha=0.5, size=20) +
theme(panel.background = element_blank(), panel.grid = element_line(color="gray", linetype=3))

Employing visual hierarchy

Employing visual hierarchy is:

  • removing clutter
  • using preattentive attributes
    • such as text size, text emphasis, color, and lines

Cluttered with no visual hierarchy.

rentalsData3 %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Longitude, y=Latitude)) +
  labs(title = "Urbana Rental Properties")

Less cluttered with little visual hierarchy.

rentalsData3 %>%
  ggplot() +
  geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Longitude, y=Latitude),color="lightgray") +
  labs(title = "Urbana Rental Properties") +
  geom_point(x=-88.227244, y=40.109399, color=rgb(19/255,41/255,75/255), alpha=0.5, size=20) +
theme(panel.background = element_blank(), panel.grid = element_line(color="gray", linetype=3))

Less cluttered with much visual hierarchy.

owners_addresses <- read_csv("https://uofi.box.com/shared/static/fh4phsjxzod704n0sigxn2iupgn5f026.csv")
## Rows: 1738 Columns: 1
## ── Column specification ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (1): name
## 
## ℹ Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
## ℹ Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
rentalsData4 <- rentalsData3 %>%
  mutate(grade_n = ifelse(Grade=="Class N", 1, Grade), 
         grade_f = ifelse(Grade=="Class F", 2, grade_n),
         grade_d = ifelse(Grade=="Class D", 3, grade_f),
         grade_c = ifelse(Grade=="Class C", 4, grade_d),
         grade_b = ifelse(Grade=="Class B", 5, grade_c),
         grade_numeric = as.numeric(ifelse(Grade=="Class A", 6, grade_b)),
         grade_prop = grade_numeric/6)

a_ids <- which(rentalsData4$Grade=="Class A")

rentalsData5 <- bind_cols(rentalsData4, owners_addresses) %>% 
  rename(OwnerAddress=name)
  

city3 <- str_split(rentalsData5$OwnerAddress, "\\n", simplify=TRUE)[,3]
city4 <- str_split(rentalsData5$OwnerAddress, "\\n", simplify=TRUE)[,4]

urbana_n<- sum(str_count(city3,"URBANA")+str_count(city4,"URBANA"))

ggplot(data=rentalsData5, mapping=aes(x=Longitude, y=Latitude)) +
  geom_point(color="lightgray") +
  labs(title = "Urbana Rental Properties") +
  geom_point(x=-88.227244, y=40.109399, color=rgb(19/255,41/255,75/255), alpha=0.5, size=20) +
  geom_point(data=filter(rentalsData5,Grade=="Class A"), color=rgb(232/255,74/255,39/255)) +
  annotate("text", x=median(range(rentalsData5$Longitude))+0.02, y=median(range(rentalsData5$Latitude))+0.026, color=rgb(232/255,74/255,39/255), label="Grade A Properties") +
  annotate("text", x=median(range(rentalsData5$Longitude))+0.02, y=median(range(rentalsData5$Latitude))+0.02, label=glue('Only {round(100*urbana_n/nrow(rentalsData4),2)}% of all Urbana\n rental properties are owned \nby people living in Urbana')) +
theme(panel.background = element_blank(), panel.grid = element_line(color="gray", linetype=3))
